    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="91"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d91">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 611.3731/43.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 9, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 417.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s telegram of
                    December 5, 1911,<note n="1" xml:id="d91fn1">Not printed.</note> and
                    instructions of November 2, in regard to the Cuban Government’s expression of
                    views concerning the reply of the Department to its request for a renewal and
                    subsequent modification of the reciprocity treaty, it is desirable that the
                    Department be informed without further delay of the views of the Cuban
                    Government.</p>
                <p>The Department’s instruction of November 2, 1911, was in response to the urgent
                    representations of the Cuban Government, and it is unable to understand the
                    delay in receiving a further reply from that Government. You are therefore
                    instructed, in case a reply has not been made when this dispatch is received, to
                    inquire formally and discreetly as to when an answer may be expected.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
